cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "Intent-as-Infrastructure: When the Compiler Is Claude"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Shatny
    given-names: Michael
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0006-2011-3258"
doi: "10.5281/zenodo.20681523"
repository-code: "https://github.com/semanticintent/intent-as-infrastructure"
abstract: >-
  Intent-as-Infrastructure (IaI) proposes a paradigm distinct from
  Methodology-as-Infrastructure: where MaI encodes how to think into
  pre-compiled deterministic runtimes, IaI encodes what to reach into as
  a bounded declarative vocabulary — delegating compilation to an AI model.
  The four required properties are: Declarative (bounded vocabulary, intent
  only), Compiled (AI model generates executable artifacts per run),
  Sovereign artifacts (every execution produces a citable, git-trackable
  finding record), and Human-as-primitive (human judgment is a first-class
  architectural element, not an optional approval step). REACH (Runtime
  Executable Adaptive C# Handler) and OCTO (On-demand Contextual Task
  Orchestrator) serve as primary case studies, validated across 18 POC
  cases and two production workflows against Windows live systems.
